    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
            <p>Not published before <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>128000</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"><certainty match=".." locus="name"/></gap> <persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Παρα_"><seg part="I"><supplied reason="lost">Π</supplied>αρα<supplied reason="lost">ιβ</supplied></seg></name></persName> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
                    <lb n="2"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character" cert="low"><certainty match=".." locus="name"/></gap> <persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Παραιβ_"><seg part="I"><unclear>Π</unclear>αρα<supplied reason="lost">ιβ</supplied></seg></name></persName> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character" cert="low"/>
                    <lb n="3"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"><certainty match=".." locus="name"/></gap> <persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Τιμ_"><seg part="I"><unclear>Τ</unclear>ιμ</seg></name></persName><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
	           </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Intraduisible.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Not usefully translatable.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Intraducibile.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="ar">
            <p>غير قابل للترجمة بشكل جيد</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
               <p>This very poor fragment seems to preserve its original size as an oblong block. If so, the inscription would have consisted in at least three personal names
                   the relation of which cannot be established. For lines 1 and 2 we have twice a typically Cyrenaican name, either <foreign xml:lang="grc">Παραιβάτας</foreign> or 
                   its short form <foreign xml:lang="grc">Πάραιβις</foreign>. Some dedications of honorific statues have condensed formulas with names opposing nominative and 
                   accusative. But it would be hazardous to push that ahead.</p>
	<p/>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
